        routeDescription: "The route takes the N137 towards Saint-Malo then branches onto the D794 to Dinan.",
        introduction: "Dinan is one of France's finest medieval cities, perched on a rocky promontory 75 metres above the River Rance. Its 2.6 km of perfectly preserved ramparts, 15th and 16th-century half-timbered houses, cobbled streets and imposing ducal castle make it a jewel of Breton heritage. The Rue du Jerzual, cobbled and steep, links the upper town to the Rance port in a spectacular descent lined with art galleries, weavers' workshops and artisan shops. Dinan's port, on the Rance, is a peaceful haven with waterside restaurants, pleasure boats and the railway viaduct spanning the valley at great height. The Fête des Remparts, held every two years in July (even years), is one of Europe's largest medieval festivals, attracting 100,000 visitors in period costumes. Taxis from Rennes are used by heritage tourists, Rance valley hikers and Rennes locals on Sunday excursions.",
        itineraire: "Your driver takes the N137 towards Saint-Malo for about 30 km, then branches onto the D794 at Québriac. The D794 crosses the Breton bocage, a rolling landscape of hedgerow-bordered meadows, oaks and beeches, with granite hamlets and slate roofs. You arrive at Dinan from the north, with a striking view of the ramparts and keep from the road. The driver drops you at the Place du Guesclin car park (at the foot of the castle) or at the Rance port as you prefer. The journey takes 45 minutes normally and can reach 1h05 in summer during the Fête des Remparts. The entire route is toll-free (departmental roads and Breton expressway).",
        conseils: "The descent down Rue du Jerzual is unmissable but the cobbles are steep — wear comfortable shoes. The rampart walk (2.6 km, free, 1h) offers exceptional views of the Rance and surrounding countryside. Dinan castle (€6) houses a local history museum with a 14th-century keep. The Rance port is ideal for lunch: Le Cantorbéry and La Fleur de Sel are good addresses. Rance river cruises (Compagnie Corsaire, €20, 2h30) sail down to Saint-Malo — a magnificent experience through wooded cliffs and manor houses. The Dinan market (Thursday mornings, Place du Guesclin) is one of Brittany's liveliest, with local produce, cider and crepes.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The TER Rennes — Dinan costs about €14 and takes 50 min to 1h. Frequency is modest (roughly one train every 2h) and Dinan station is a 15-min walk from the centre. The Illenoo bus (line 9a) links Rennes to Dinan for about €5 in 1h15. The TaxiNeo taxi at €70 — €90 offers flexibility and door-to-door service, essential if you also want to reach the Rance port or explore the surroundings. For 3-4 passengers (€18-30 per person), the taxi is very competitive against the TER.",
