        introduction: "Concarneau is a uniquely maritime town, famous for its Ville Close — a fortified citadel built on an islet in the middle of the harbour, linked to the mainland by a drawbridge and enclosed by 14th-century ramparts. Enter through a monumental gateway to discover cobbled lanes, artisan shops, galleries and creperies in a preserved medieval setting. Concarneau is also France's 3rd fishing port (tuna, sardine, langoustine) and the landing port for tropical deep-sea fishing. The Fishing Museum, housed in a former arsenal, traces the history of this founding activity. Each summer, the Fête des Filets Bleus (August), one of Brittany's oldest festivals (1905), fills the town with music, Breton dances and traditional costume parades. The marina, modern fish auction and Cabellou beaches complete this appealing town's offer. Taxis from Rennes are popular with holidaymakers, fishing enthusiasts and Filets Bleus festival-goers.",
        itineraire: "From Rennes, your driver takes the N24 towards Lorient, crosses the Forest of Brocéliande and Ploërmel, then joins the N165 at Baud. The N165 runs through southern Morbihan then enters the Finistère at Quimperlé. At Rosporden (20 km after Quimperlé), you leave the N165 for the D783 towards Concarneau (15 km). The road descends towards the coast through apple orchards (cider), rolling countryside and granite hamlets. Arrival in Concarneau offers a spectacular view of the harbour and the fortified Ville Close. The journey takes 2h15 normally and can reach 2h45 in summer. The entire route is toll-free.",
        conseils: "The Ville Close is Concarneau's heart: walk the ramparts (free, 30 min) for a complete panorama of the harbour, roadstead and trawlers. The Fishing Museum (€6, 1h) is fascinating, with a trawler afloat to explore. The Concarneau fish auction can be visited with a guided tour (tourist office, mornings, €8) — a fascinating spectacle at 6am when trawlers land their catch. Cabellou and Sables Blancs are Concarneau's finest beaches. For seafood, l'Amiral (harbour, facing the Ville Close) and Le Chalut are reliable choices. The Fête des Filets Bleus (mid-August) is a joyful event with bagadoù concerts, fest-noz ceilidhs and its famous grilled sardine tasting. Pont-Aven, the painters' village (Gauguin), is 15 km away — an ideal taxi combination.",
